Type inference — what the compiler does for free.

Scala is statically typed, but the compiler does most of the typing work for you. For a val, the compiler reads the right-hand side, computes its type, and uses that as the type of the binding. No annotation needed.

Most of the code you read and write will look like that, with no explicit types in sight. Write val a equals forty-two, and the compiler infers integer. Bind a decimal and it infers double. Bind a quoted string and it infers string. Bind a list of whole numbers and it infers list of integer. Bind a grouping of an integer, a string, and a decimal, and it infers a three-element tuple of those types.

The honest rule is this. Let inference handle local values inside method bodies, but annotate every public-facing signature. A method's parameter and return types are part of its contract — hide them, and a later change to the body can silently change the type the rest of the world depends on. So always annotate the return type of a method that other code calls.

That rule covers the common case. The next section covers the three specific places where you should write the type even when inference would otherwise succeed.
